\begin{equation}
= \frac{1}{2}[p((n-1) \Delta, k \tau)+p((n+1) \Delta, k \tau)-2 p(n \Delta, k \tau)] \\
-\Delta \cdot[p((n+1) \Delta, k \tau) \cdot \alpha((n+1) \Delta)-p((n-1) \Delta, k \tau) \cdot \alpha((n-1) \Delta)]
\end{equation}
Divide by  [mathjaxinline]\tau [/mathjaxinline] and set the limit  [mathjaxinline]\tau \rightarrow 0, \Delta \rightarrow 0 [/mathjaxinline]
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial p(n \Delta, k \tau)}{\partial t}=\frac{\Delta^{2}}{2 \tau} \frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial x^{2}} p(n \Delta, k \tau)-\frac{2 \Delta^{2}}{\tau} \frac{\partial}{\partial x}[\alpha(n \Delta) \cdot p(n \Delta, k \tau)]
\end{equation}
With [mathjaxinline]D=\frac{\Delta^{2}}{2 \tau}, x=n \Delta, t=k \tau, [/mathjaxinline] the master equation for  [mathjaxinline] p(x, t) [/mathjaxinline] is:
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial p(x, t)}{\partial t}=-4 D \frac{\partial}{\partial x}[\alpha(x) \cdot p(x, t)]+D \frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial x^{2}} p(x, t)
\end{equation}
Compare with Smoluchowski equation:
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial P}{\partial t}=-\frac{1}{m \gamma} \frac{\partial}{\partial x}[F(x) \cdot P(x, t)]+D \frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial x^{2}} P
\end{equation}
We identify [mathjaxinline]F(x)=4 D m \gamma \alpha(x) [/mathjaxinline].

